In Unreal Engine 5, to pass a function to a method that will be used on an FTimerHandle with SetTimer, you can use a delegate called FTimerDelegate. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this:

1. In your header file (.h), declare your function you want to call. Make sure it takes no parameters and returns void:

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AYourActor : public AActor
{
    GENERATED_BODY()

public:
    // Other member variables and functions here

    UFUNCTION()
    void YourFunction();
};
```

2. Implement your function in the corresponding .cpp file:

```cpp
void AYourActor::YourFunction()
{
    // Your implementation here
}
```

3. Create a timer and pass the function to it using an FTimerDelegate:

In BeginPlay() or in any other function where you want to create the timer, initialize an FTimerHandle and an FTimerDelegate.

```cpp
FTimerHandle YourTimerHandle;
FTimerDelegate YourTimerDelegate;
```

4. Bind the delegate to your function:

```cpp
YourTimerDelegate.BindUFunction(this, FName("YourFunction"));
```

5. Set the timer with the delegate and the desired time interval and looping:

```cpp
GetWorld()->GetTimerManager().SetTimer(YourTimerHandle, YourTimerDelegate, Rate, true);
```

For example, if you want to call `YourFunction()` every 2 seconds in a loop, set the Rate to 2.0f and set the last parameter to true. If it's not looping, set it to false.

That's it - now, your function will be called based on the interval and looping specified in the SetTimer() function.

To pass a parameter to the timer delegate, you can use a slightly different delegate type called `FTimerDynamicDelegate`. Here's how to set that up:

1. Declare your function in the header file (.h). This time, the function should take a single parameter of the desired type. In this example, we'll use an integer parameter:

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AYourActor : public AActor
{
    GENERATED_BODY()

public:
    // Other member variables and functions here

    UFUNCTION()
    void YourFunction(int32 SomeValue);
};
```

2. Implement your function in the corresponding .cpp file:

```cpp
void AYourActor::YourFunction(int32 SomeValue)
{
    // Your implementation here
}
```

3. Create a timer and pass the function to it using an FTimerDynamicDelegate:

In BeginPlay() or in any other function where you want to create the timer, initialize an FTimerHandle and an FTimerDynamicDelegate.

```cpp
FTimerHandle YourTimerHandle;
FTimerDynamicDelegate YourTimerDelegate;
```

4. Bind the delegate to your function with the parameter value:

```cpp
int32 ParameterValue = 42;
YourTimerDelegate.BindUFunction(this, FName("YourFunction"), ParameterValue);
```

5. Set the timer with the delegate and the desired time interval and looping:

```cpp
GetWorld()->GetTimerManager().SetTimer(YourTimerHandle, YourTimerDelegate, Rate, true);
```

Now, your function will be called with the specified parameter value based on the interval and looping defined in the SetTimer() function.

