1. Add a new gameplay tag for your targeting ability in your GameplayTags ini file:

```ini
ExampleTagCategory.TargetingAbility
```

2. Add the newly created tag to your targeting ability. You can do this in the Ability's constructor (C++) or by editing the Ability Tags in the Ability's Blueprint.

For example, in C++:

```cpp
UMyTargetingAbility::UMyTargetingAbility()
{
    // Other settings here
    AbilityTags.AddTag(FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag("ExampleTagCategory.TargetingAbility");
}
```

3. In your auto-attack Ability or wherever you are handling the auto-attack logic, before starting the auto-attack or before sending the auto-attack Gameplay Event, use the `GetActivatableAbilities()` function to get all the abilities from the Ability System Component or Ability System Interface of the target actor, and check if your targeting ability is active. If it is active, don't start the auto-attack:

```cpp
bool bShouldAutoAttack = true;
if (ActorWithAbilitySystem != nullptr)
{
    TArray<UGameplayAbility*> ActivatableAbilities;
    ActorWithAbilitySystem->GetActivatableAbilities(ActivatableAbilities);

    FGameplayTag TargetingAbilityTag = FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag("ExampleTagCategory.TargetingAbility");
    for (UGameplayAbility* Ability : ActivatableAbilities)
    {
        if (Ability->GetCurrentActivationInfo().GetActivationCount() > 0 &&
            Ability->AbilityTags.HasTagExact(TargetingAbilityTag))
        {
            bShouldAutoAttack = false;
            break;
        }
    }
}

if (bShouldAutoAttack)
{
    // Carry out auto-attack logic
}
```

By using this approach, the auto-attack should only start if the Targeting Ability is not active. Consequently, when you cast a targeting ability, the auto-attack should not be triggered, resulting in the desired behavior.

In the latest version of GAS, getting the activation count of an ability directly is no longer available. Instead, you need to get the 'InstancePerActor' instancing policy abilities from the AbilitySystemComponent, and check the Abilities' Activation State to know if they are active or not.

Follow these steps to check if a specific ability is active:

1. Include the required headers in the file where the code will be placed:

```cpp
#include "AbilitySystemComponent.h"
#include "GameplayTagContainer.h"
```

2. Get the abilities with the `'InstancePerActor'` instancing policy from the AbilitySystemComponent:

```cpp
TArray<FGameplayAbilitySpec> InstancedAbilities = AbilitySystemComponent->GetActivatableAbilities();
```

3. Iterate through the `InstancedAbilities` array, and check if the specific ability is active by comparing its tags with a predefined tag and checking its activation state:

```cpp
bool bIsTargetingAbilityActive = false;
FGameplayTag TargetingAbilityTag = FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag("ExampleTagCategory.TargetingAbility");

for (const FGameplayAbilitySpec& AbilitySpec : InstancedAbilities)
{
    UGameplayAbility* InstancedAbility = AbilitySpec.GetPrimaryInstance();
    if (InstancedAbility != nullptr && InstancedAbility->AbilityTags.HasTagExact(TargetingAbilityTag))
    {
        if (AbilitySpec.ActiveCount > 0)
        {
            bIsTargetingAbilityActive = true;
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

Now, the variable `bIsTargetingAbilityActive` will be true if the Targeting Ability is active and false otherwise. You can use this boolean value to conditionally trigger your auto-attack or other behaviors in your game.

